<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="transcription">Transcription</h2><ul><li><p>A <b>gene</b> is a <b>sequence of nucleotide bases </b>in a DNA molecule that <b>codes for the production of a specific sequence of amino acids</b>, that in turn make up a <b>specific polypeptide</b> (<b>protein</b>)</p></li><li><p>This process of protein synthesis occurs in <b>two stages</b>:</p><ul><li><p><b>Transcription</b> – <b>DNA</b> is transcribed and an <b>mRNA </b>(messenger RNA)<b> </b>molecule is produced</p></li><li><p><b>Translation</b> – <b>mRNA</b> is translated and an <b>amino acid sequence</b> is produced</p><ul><li><p>mRNA is a single-stranded molecule made up of many <b>RNA nucleotides </b>joined together</p></li><li><p>The role of mRNA is to carry the information encoded in the DNA from the nucleus to the site of translation on ribosomes</p></li><li><p>RNA is similar to DNA except for the following</p><ul><li><p>RNA contains a <b>ribose</b> sugar while DNA contains deoxyribose</p></li><li><p>RNA is usually <b>single-stranded</b> while DNA is double-stranded</p></li><li><p>RNA contains the base <b>uracil</b> instead of the DNA base thymine</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="transcription">Transcription</h4><ul><li><p>This stage of protein synthesis occurs in the <b>nucleus</b> of the cell</p></li><li><p>Part of a DNA molecule unwinds and the hydrogen bonds between the complementary base pairs break</p></li><li><p>This <b>exposes the gene to be transcribed</b> (the gene from which a particular polypeptide will be produced)</p></li><li><p>A <b>complimentary</b> copy of the code from the gene is made by building a <b>single-stranded nucleic acid molecule known as mRNA</b> </p><ul><li><p>This reaction is catalysed by <span class="popovers" data-content="Enzyme that joins together nucleotides to form messenger RNA during transcription." data-title="RNA Polymerase" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition"><b>RNA polymerase</b></span></p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Free activated RNA nucleotides</b> pair up, via hydrogen bonds, with their <b>complementary</b> bases on the exposed strand of the <b>‘unzipped’ DNA molecule</b></p></li><li><p>The sugar-phosphate groups of these RNA nucleotides are then bonded together in a reaction catalysed by the enzyme RNA polymerase to form the sugar-phosphate backbone of the mRNA molecule</p></li><li><p>When the gene has been transcribed and the mRNA molecule is complete, the hydrogen bonds between the mRNA and DNA strands break and the <b>double-stranded DNA molecule reforms</b></p></li><li><p>The <b>mRNA molecule then leaves the nucleus </b>via a pore in the nuclear envelope</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Transcription in the nucleus" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="836" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Transcription-in-the-nucleus.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The transcription stage of protein synthesis - DNA is transcribed and an mRNA molecule is produced</b></i></p><h4 id="anti-sense-and-sense-strands">Anti-sense and sense strands</h4><ul><li><p>In the <b>transcription</b> stage of protein synthesis, free RNA nucleotides pair up with the exposed bases on the DNA molecule</p></li><li><p>RNA nucleotides only pair with the bases on<b> one strand of the DNA molecule</b></p><ul><li><p>This strand of the DNA molecule is known as the <b>antisense</b> or <b>template strand</b> (or the <b>transcribed strand</b>) and it is used to produce the <b>mRNA molecule</b></p></li><li><p>The other strand is known as the <b>sense</b> or <b>coding strand</b> (or the <b>non-template</b> or <b>non-transcribed strand</b>)</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>RNA polymerase</b> moves along the template strand in the <b>3' to 5' direction</b></p><ul><li><p>This means that the <b>mRNA</b> molecule grows in the <b>5' to 3' direction</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Because the mRNA is formed by complementary pairing with the DNA template strand, the mRNA molecule contains the <b>exact same sequence of nucleotides</b> as the DNA <b>coding strand</b> (although the mRNA will contain <b>uracil</b> instead of <b>thymine</b>)</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Process of Transcription" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="681" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Process-of-Transcription.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Process-of-Transcription.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The antisense strand of DNA is the one that is transcribed into mRNA</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>Be careful – <b>DNA</b> polymerase is the enzyme involved in DNA replication; <b>RNA</b> polymerase is the enzyme involved in <b>transcription</b> – don’t get these confused.</p><p>Note the use of <b>sense</b> and <b>anti-sense strands</b> in transcription can be replaced with non-transcribed and transcribed/template strands respectively.</p><p>The mRNA strand will have the same base sequence as the sense strand <b>except</b> on RNA the base <b>U</b>racil replaces <b>T</b>hymine from the DNA strand.</p></div></div></div></div>